ending”. But this is not what the Sruti says.}
\par
\SKT{\it naiva v\=ac\=a na manas\=a pr\=aptu\.m \'sakyo na cak\,su\,s\=a, ast\=iti
bruvato'nyatra katha\.m tadupalabhyate. 12. }
\par\sitem{12.} “Not with the mind has man the power to get God, no, nor
through speech, nor by the eye. Unless one says `He is', how can one
become sensible of Him?
\par
\SKT{\it ast\=ityevopalabdhavyastattvabh\=avena cobhayo\,h,
ast\=ityevopalabdhasya tattvabh\=ava\,h pras\=idati. 13. }
\par\sitem{13.} “One must apprehend God in the concept `He is' and also in
His essential: but when he has grasped Him as the `Is', then the essential of
God dawns upon a man.
\par
\SKT{\it yad\=a sarve pramucyante k\=am\=a ye'sya h\,rdi \'srit\=a\,h, atha martyo'm\,rto
bhavatyatra brahma sama\'snute. 14. }
\par\sitem{14.} “When every desire that finds lodging in the heart of man,
has been loosened from its moorings, then this mortal puts on immortality:
even here he tastes God, in this human body.
\par
\SKT{\it yad\=a sarve prabhidyante h\,rdayasyeha granthaya\,h, atha
martyo'm\,rto bhavatyet\=avaddhyanu\'s\=asanam. 15.
